In [42]:
y = data['target']
X = data.drop(columns='target')

X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.3, random_state=42)

model = xgboost.XGBRegressor()
model.fit(X_train, y_train)

Features analysis¶

By the SHAP (SHapley Additive exPlanations) tool we analyse the more relevant features in the model

In [43]:
shap.initjs()
Out[43]:
In [44]:
explainer = shap.TreeExplainer(model)
shap_values = explainer.shap_values(X_train)

Analysis of the features and their importance

In [203]:
shap.summary_plot(shap_values, X_train, max_display= 10)
Out[203]:

We see by this plot the impact of 10 more relevant features in our model, being:.

  • NY.GDP.MKTP.KD.ZG $\;$ -------> $\;$GDP growth (annual %)
  • Year $\;\;\;\;\;\;\;\;\;\;\;\;\;\;\;\;$$\;\;\;\;\;\;$ -------> $\;$Year
  • FP.CPI.TOTL.ZG $\;\;\;\;\;\;\;$ -------> $\;$Inflation, consumer prices (annual %)
  • NY.ADJ.AEDU.GN.ZS $\;\;$-------> $\;$Adjusted savings: education expenditure (% of GNI)
  • NV.SRV.TETC.KD.ZG $\;\;\;$-------> $\;$Services, etc., value added (annual % growth)
  • NY.GDP.PCAP.CD $\;\;\;\;\;\;$ ------->$\;$ GDP per capita (current US dollars)
  • NV.AGR.TOTL.KD.ZG $\;\;$-------> $\;$Agriculture, forestry, and fishing, value added (annual % growth)
  • NY.GDP.DEFL.KD.ZG $\;\;$-------> $\;$Inflation, GDP deflator (annual %)
  • IT.CEL.SETS $\;\;\;\;\;\;$ $\;\;\;\;\;\;$-------> $\;$Mobile cellular subscriptions
  • TX.VAL.MRCH.XD.WD $\;$-------> $\;$Export value index

Some features are obvious to be in this list, like GDP per capita or Inflation but other like number of Mobile cellular subscriptions may be not so obvious. However this list of more relevant features seems to make sense as we are predicting GDP growth.

In this plot we see the average impact of most relevant features on our model output.
Of course the GDP growth is the most important but the year seem to be important too.

In [36]:
expected_value = explainer.expected_value
print(f"Explainer expected value: {expected_value}")

select = range(10)
features = X_test.iloc[select]
features_display = X.loc[features.index]

with warnings.catch_warnings():
    warnings.simplefilter("ignore")
    shap_values = explainer.shap_values(features)[1]
    shap_interaction_values = explainer.shap_interaction_values(features)
if isinstance(shap_interaction_values, list):
    shap_interaction_values = shap_interaction_values[1]

Explainer expected value: 4.204092025756836

This plot above displays the ordered features importance over the predicted GDP growth. At the top of the plot is shown the predicted value and the effect on how each feature contribute to the predicted expected value. We can see how at the end it will converge to the expected value although we only show the 180 morerelevant features.

In [37]:

Out[37]:

Conclusions¶

So we can conclude that although we have a huge number - 282 exactly - of features not all of them have the same relevance when we are training and testing a model with Extreme Gradient Boosting. However, this more relevant features are the one as we expected to be, all of them related with economic and social characteristics. Also, some dimensional features as the Year one seem to have a different relevance in the GDP growth, a thing that we expected to happen as well.
